# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: animal-rights
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:animal-rights/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:animal-rights/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:animal-rights/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:animal-rights/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:animal-rights/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:animal-rights/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:animal-rights/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner obtained his M.D. from Yale Medical School in 1909 and received the Campbell Gold Medal for the highest rank on his examination and the Keese Prize for his thesis.
[src:animal-rights/a-fleshless-diet] In 1916, Buttner was described by the editor of the *Journal of the American Medical Association* as a "recognized representative in the literature of vegetarianism." He argued for vegetarianism from a scientific basis.
[src:animal-rights/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner practiced medicine in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:animal-rights/a-fleshless-diet] He was a member of the New Haven County Medical Association.
[src:animal-rights/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner is best known for his vegetarian book *A Fleshless Diet*, published in 1910.
[src:animal-rights/a-fleshless-diet] It was widely reviewed in medical journals with a mixed response.
[src:animal-rights/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner argued that comparative anatomy and nutrition demonstrates that man is suited for a fleshless diet and that meat is dangerous and unnecessary.
[src:animal-rights/a-fleshless-diet] His recommended diet consisted of vegetables, eggs and milk.
[src:animal-rights/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner wrote that "It is not illogical for vegetarians to use milk and eggs, as these animal products are distinctly less toxic than meat and also less likely to be disease-laden.
[src:animal-rights/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *American Physical Education Review*, praised the book for compiling useful dietetic research but commented that it failed to show scientific discretion in the selected material.
[src:animal-rights/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *Journal of the American Medical Association* recommended the book as a reference work whether or not one accepts Buttner's conclusions.
[src:animal-rights/a-fleshless-diet] A review in *The Medical Standard*, noted that the book was a "piece of special pleading for the propaganda which it is designed to promote […] We may say this, however, for Dr.
[src:animal-rights/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:animal-rights/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:animal-rights/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:animal-rights/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:animal-rights/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:animal-rights/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:animal-rights/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:animal-rights/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:animal-rights/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:animal-rights/a-sacred-duty] The film opens with footage of a NASA rocket launch, an animation of the Solar System, and a quote from Deuteronomy 30:19 about choosing between life and death (illustrated with images of Earth as seen from space, contrasted with an exploding atom bomb).
[src:animal-rights/a-sacred-duty] This is followed by a statement that humanity has not been caring for the planet properly according to Jewish teachings, which precedes a section about ancient Jewish texts and sacred words that provide "specific instructions on how to be custodians of the world in which we live".
[src:animal-rights/a-sacred-duty] Throughout the film, quotes from the Torah are contrasted with the various environmental threats facing humanity today; the quotes are also illustrated with close-ups of Hebrew scrolls, Jews praying, and scenes of nature.
[src:animal-rights/a-sacred-duty] The Earth is again seen from space and the camera moves in to focus on Israel, which the narrator cites as a microcosm of current global problems related to air and water pollution, overpopulation, climate change, and health concerns.
[src:animal-rights/a-sacred-duty] The film moves on to look at global problems, with scenes shot all over the world.
[src:animal-rights/a-sacred-duty] The focus then shifts to the United States, where all the relevant issues are discussed in detail.
[src:animal-rights/a-sacred-duty] Reference is made to *Livestock's Long Shadow*, a 2006 report by the Food and Agriculture Organization which claimed that livestock agriculture produces more greenhouse gases than all of the world's vehicles combined.
[src:animal-rights/a-sacred-duty] Next comes a brief presentation, illustrated with simple animated charts, on how meat production is an inefficient way to produce food for a hungry world.
[src:animal-rights/a-sacred-duty] This moves into footage of animal abuse on feedlots and in factory farms, and the pollution produced by these facilities.
[src:animal-rights/a-sacred-duty] The film then focuses on the advantages of vegetarianism for reducing pollution and solving world hunger.
[src:animal-rights/a-sacred-duty] With a change of diet toward vegetarianism, the film asserts that many of these environmental and health problems can be solved.
[src:animal-rights/a-sacred-duty] After some fast-moving images of people and nature accompanied by music, the film ends with the same statement from Deuteronomy about "life and death" being narrated over a shot of a sunrise.
[src:animal-rights/a-sacred-duty] The idea for the film was inspired by the writings of Richard H.
[src:animal-rights/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz (*Judaism and Vegetarianism*, *Judaism and Global Survival*, etc.) who also served as associate producer.
[src:animal-rights/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz had seen the Christian Vegetarian Association's 2006 film, *Honoring God's Creation*, and felt that a similar film would be effective in the Jewish community.
[src:animal-rights/a-sacred-duty] At the time, he envisioned the film to be about 30 minutes long, though the final film ended up being 60 minutes long.
[src:animal-rights/a-sacred-duty] Production began in 2005 with a basic proposal and outline in the JVNA's newsletter, along with a statement that Lionel Friedberg was willing to make the film for "a very low fee, basically to cover his costs".
[src:animal-rights/a-sacred-duty] The film was funded by the JVNA through private contributions.
[src:animal-rights/a-sacred-duty] Preliminary drafts of the script were circulated among members of the JVNA advisory committee and others for input, after which the script went through numerous revisions.
[src:animal-rights/a-sacred-duty] Meanwhile, Schwartz and Friedberg set about interviewing possible participants and filming footage of nature in both Israel and the United States.
[src:animal-rights/a-sacred-duty] The showing of slaughterhouse footage was controversial, with some members of a test audience in Staten Island seeing it as propaganda.
[src:animal-rights/a-sacred-duty] Friedberg recalled, "Richard and I were accused of making a propaganda film for the vegetarian movement.
[src:animal-rights/a-sacred-duty] We were accused of showing 'horrors that are impossible to watch'." However, he maintained that the graphic footage was necessary.
[src:animal-rights/a-sacred-duty] In October and November 2007, *A Sacred Duty* was released direct-to-video and on DVD, with public showings in both Israel and the United States.
[src:animal-rights/a-sacred-duty] Over 35,000 copies were distributed free of charge to synagogues, educational institutions, and individuals, complete with permission to show the film without having to pay the filmmakers any royalties.
[src:animal-rights/a-sacred-duty] In addition, permission was granted to the public to duplicate and distribute the film free of charge.
[src:animal-rights/a-sacred-duty] Numerous short excerpts from the film were edited and re-posted by various YouTube users, and the full version became available on YouTube in January 2008.
[src:animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:animal-rights/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] The resultant theory was challenged and refined several times in the decades following its original publication in 1971.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] A significant reappraisal was published in the 1985 essay "Justice as Fairness" and the 2001 book *Justice as Fairness: A Restatement* in which Rawls further developed his two central principles for his discussion of justice.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] Together, they assert that society should be structured to provide the greatest possible degree of liberty to its members, limited only by the principle that one individual's liberty must not infringe upon the liberty of others.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] Secondly, inequalities – either social or economic – are only to be allowed if the worst off will be better off than they might be under an equal distribution.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] Finally, if an inequality is to be justified on the grounds of its benefits, it must not create additional barriers for those without resources to access positions of power, such as public office.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] In *A Theory of Justice,* Rawls argues for a principled reconciliation of liberty and equality that is meant to apply to the basic structure of a well-ordered society.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] Central to this effort is an account of the circumstances of justice, inspired by David Hume, and a fair choice situation for parties facing such circumstances, similar to some of Immanuel Kant's views.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] Principles of justice are sought to guide the conduct of the parties.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] These parties are recognized to face moderate scarcity, and they are neither naturally altruistic nor purely egoistic.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] They have ends which they seek to advance but prefer to advance them through cooperation with others on mutually acceptable terms.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls offers a model of a fair choice situation (the original position with its veil of ignorance) within which parties would hypothetically choose mutually acceptable principles of justice.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] Under such constraints, Rawls believes that parties would find his favoured principles of justice to be especially attractive, winning out over varied alternatives, including utilitarian and right-wing libertarian accounts.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls belongs to the social contract tradition, although he takes a different view from that of previous thinkers.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] Specifically, Rawls develops what he claims are principles of justice through the use of an artificial device or thought experiment he calls the *Original position*; in which, everyone decides principles of justice from behind a veil of ignorance.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] [N]o one knows his place in society, his class position or social status, nor does anyone know his fortune in the distribution of natural assets and abilities, his intelligence, strength, and the like.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] I shall even assume that the parties do not know their conceptions of the good or their special psychological propensities.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] The principles of justice are chosen behind a veil of ignorance.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] They are the principles that rational and free persons concerned to further their own interests would accept in an initial position of equality as defining the fundamentals of the terms of their association.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] If an individual does not know how he will end up in his own conceived society, he is likely not going to privilege any one class of people, but rather develop a scheme of justice that treats all fairly.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] In particular, Rawls claims that those in the *Original Position* would adopt two principles, the second of which is a maximin strategy which would maximize the prospects of the least well-off.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls bases his *Original Position* on a "thin theory of the good" which he says "explains the rationality underlying choice of principles in the Original Position".
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] A full theory of the good follows after we derive principles from the original position.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls claims that the parties in the original position would adopt two such principles, which would then govern the assignment of rights and duties and regulate the distribution of social and economic advantages across society.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] The difference principle permits inequalities in the distribution of goods only if those inequalities benefit the worst-off members of society.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls believes that this principle would be a rational choice for the representatives in the original position for the following reason: Each member of society has an equal claim on their society's goods.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] Natural attributes should not affect this claim, so the basic right of any individual, before further considerations are taken into account, must be to an equal share in material wealth.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] What, then, could justify unequal distribution?
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls argues that inequality is acceptable only if it is to the advantage of those who are worst-off.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] The agreement that stems from the original position is both *hypothetical* and *ahistorical*.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] It is hypothetical in the sense that the principles to be derived are what the parties would, under certain legitimating conditions, agree to, not what they have agreed to.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls seeks to use an argument that the principles of justice are what *would* be agreed upon if people were in the hypothetical situation of the original position and that those principles have moral weight as a result of that.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] It is ahistorical in the sense that it is not supposed that the agreement has ever been, or indeed could ever have been, derived in the real world outside of carefully limited experimental exercises.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls modifies and develops the principles of justice throughout his book.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] The first principle is often called the *greatest equal liberty principle*.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] Rawls orders the principles of justice lexically, as follows: **1**, **2b**, **2a**.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] The *greatest equal liberty principle* takes priority, followed by the *equal opportunity principle* and finally the *difference principle*.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] The first principle must be satisfied before 2b, and 2b must be satisfied before 2a.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] The *greatest equal liberty principle* is mainly concerned with the distribution of rights and liberties.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] His position is at least in some sense egalitarian, with a provision that inequalities are allowed when they benefit the least advantaged.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] An important consequence of Rawls' view is that inequalities can actually be just, as long as they are to the benefit of the least well off.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] His argument for this position rests heavily on the claim that morally arbitrary factors (for example, the family one is born into) should not determine one's life chances or opportunities.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] Further, the just savings principle requires that some sort of material respect is left for future generations.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] Although Rawls is ambiguous about what this means, it can generally be understood as "a contribution to those coming later".
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] The stipulation in 2b is lexically prior to that in 2a.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] In 1972, *A Theory of Justice* was reviewed in *The New York Times Book Review* by Marshall Cohen, who described the work as "magisterial," and suggested that Rawls' use of the techniques of analytic philosophy made the book the "most formidable" defense of the social contract tradition to date.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] Michael Sandel criticized Rawls in *Liberalism and the Limits of Justice* (1982), arguing that Rawls encourages people to think about justice while divorced from the values and aspirations that define who they are as persons and that allow people to determine what justice is.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] Susan Moller Okin wrote in *Justice, Gender, and the Family* (1989) that Rawls had provided "the most influential of all twentieth-century theories of justice", but criticized him for failing to account for the injustices and hierarchies embedded in familial relations.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] In his book *Black Rights / White Wrongs*, philosopher Charles W.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] Mills critiques the underlying assumptions of Rawls’s work as inherently white, and thus subject to glaring blind spots.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] The economist Amartya Sen has raised concerns over Rawls' emphasis on primary social goods, arguing in *Inequality Reexamined* (1992) that we should attend not only to the distribution of primary goods, but also how effectively people are able to use those goods to pursue their ends.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] Norman Daniels has wondered why health care should not be treated as a primary good, and some of his subsequent work has addressed this question, arguing for a right to health care within a broadly Rawlsian framework.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] Sen critiques and attempts to revitalize *A Theory of Justice* in *The Idea of Justice* (2009).
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] He credits Rawls for revitalizing the interest in the ideas of what justice means and the stress put on fairness, objectivity, equality of opportunity, removal of poverty, and freedom.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] However, Sen, as part of his general critique of the contractarian tradition, states that ideas about a perfectly just world do not help redress actual existing inequality.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] Sen faults Rawls for overemphasizing institutions as guarantors of justice and not considering the effects of human behaviour on the institutions' ability to maintain a just society.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] Sen believes Rawls understates the difficulty in getting everyone in society to adhere to the norms of a just society.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] He also claims that Rawls' position that there be only one possible outcome of the reflective equilibrium behind the veil of ignorance is misguided.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] In contrast to Rawls, Sen believes that multiple conflicting, yet just, principles may arise and that this undermines the multistep processes that Rawls laid out as leading to a perfectly just society.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] Cohen argued that Rawls's principles of justice are influenced by assumptions about social institutions and human behaviour.
[src:animal-rights/a-theory-of-justice] He maintained that a theory of justice should identify principles that are fundamentally just independently of practical considerations, and therefore contended that Rawls's account was not a theory of justice in the strict sense.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Broadly speaking, and particularly in popular discourse, the term "animal rights" is often used synonymously with "animal protection" or "animal liberation".
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] More narrowly, "animal rights" refers to the idea that many animals have fundamental rights to be treated with respect as individuals—rights to life, liberty, and freedom from torture—that may not be overridden by considerations of aggregate welfare.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Like human rights, animal rights center on the notion of freedom.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Many animal rights advocates oppose assigning moral value and fundamental protections on the basis of species membership alone.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] They consider this idea, known as speciesism, a prejudice as irrational as any other, and hold that animals should not be considered property or used as food, clothing, entertainment, or beasts of burden merely because they are not human.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Cultural traditions such as Jainism, Taoism, Hinduism, Buddhism, Shinto, and animism also espouse varying forms of animal rights.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] In parallel to the debate about moral rights, North American law schools now often teach animal law, and several legal scholars, such as Steven M.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Francione, support extending basic legal rights and personhood to nonhuman animals.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] The animals most often considered in arguments for personhood are apes, especially great apes.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Some animal-rights academics support this because it would break the species barrier, but others oppose it because it predicates moral value on mental complexity rather than sentience alone.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] As of November 2019, 29 countries had enacted bans on hominoid experimentation; Argentina granted captive orangutans basic human rights in 2014.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Outside of primates, animal-rights discussions most often address the status of mammals (compare charismatic megafauna).
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Other animals (considered less sentient) have gained less attention—insects relatively little (outside Jainism) and animal-like bacteria hardly any.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] The vast majority of animals have no legally recognised rights.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Critics of animal rights argue that nonhuman animals are unable to enter into a social contract, and thus cannot have rights, a view summarised by the philosopher Roger Scruton, who writes that only humans have duties, and therefore only humans have rights.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Certain forms of animal-rights activism, such as the destruction of fur farms and of animal laboratories by the Animal Liberation Front, have attracted criticism, including from within the animal-rights movement itself, and prompted the U.S.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Congress to enact laws, including the Animal Enterprise Terrorism Act, allowing the prosecution of this sort of activity as terrorism.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Hemachandra, a 12th-century Jain scholar and monk, achieved a significant political victory for vegetarianism in Indian history.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] He converted King Kumarapala of the Chaulukya dynasty (who ruled present-day Gujarat and surrounding areas) to Jainism.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Under Hemachandra's guidance, Kumarapala issued sweeping imperial edicts (*amari-ghoshana*) that banned the slaughter of animals.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] This alliance is historically responsible for cementing Gujarat as the geographic epicenter of strict vegetarian cuisine in India.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] In the 16th century, the Jain monk Hiravijaya Suri was invited to the court of the Mughal Emperor Akbar.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Through philosophical discussions about nonviolence, the monk persuaded Akbar to issue imperial edicts (*farmans*) that enforced animal welfare across the empire.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] These edicts banned the slaughter of animals for several months of the year, prohibited fishing in specific sacred lakes, and mandated the release of thousands of caged birds.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] This represents one of the earliest recorded instances of state-enforced animal welfare and dietary restrictions at the imperial level in Indian history.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Jain communities established large-scale systems for animal welfare long ago.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Jain merchants funded the creation of *panjrapoles*—specialized animal shelters and hospitals designed to care for sick, old, or rescued livestock and birds.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] The motivation for these shelters was not ethical philosophy, but the core Jain religious belief that committing violence against any living creature directly harms a person's soul and spiritual purity.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Serious discussion about animal rights began in 18th- and 19th-century Europe, but respect for animals can be found in most cultures and traditions, including Hinduism, Buddhism, Jainism, and some African and Indigenous cultures.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] In the Western world, Aristotle viewed animals as lacking reason and existing for human use, though other ancient philosophers believed animals deserved gentle treatment.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Major religious traditions, chiefly Indian or Dharmic religions, opposed animal cruelty.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] While scholars like Descartes saw animals as unconscious automata, and Kant denied direct duties to animals, Jeremy Bentham emphasized their capacity to suffer.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] The publications of Charles Darwin eventually eroded the Cartesian view of animals.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Darwin noted the mental and emotional continuity between humans and animals, suggesting the possibility of animal suffering.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] The anti-vivisection movement emerged in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, driven significantly by women.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] From the 1970s onward, growing scholarly and activist interest in animal treatment has aimed to raise awareness and reform laws to improve animal rights and human–animal relationships.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] These can be illustrated by the behavior of exploited animals (as in farming, labor, scientific laboratories), particularly their resistance to manipulation and confinement, including attempts to escape when opportunities arise.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] For some the basis of animal rights is in religion or animal worship (or in general nature worship), with some religions banning killing any animal.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] In other religions animals are considered unclean.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Hindu and Buddhist societies abandoned animal sacrifice and embraced vegetarianism from the 3rd century BCE.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] One of the most important sanctions of the Jain, Hindu, and Buddhist faiths is the concept of ahimsa, or refraining from the destruction of life.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] According to Buddhism, humans do not deserve preferential treatment over other living beings.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] The Dharmic interpretation of this doctrine prohibits the killing of any living being.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] These Indian religions' dharmic beliefs are reflected in the ancient Indian works of the Tolkāppiyam and Tirukkural, which contain passages that extend the idea of nonviolence to all living beings.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] The historical codification of Jain vegetarianism as a universal mandate for the lay community is sociologically anchored in the narrative of Neminatha, the 22nd *tirthankara*.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] According to Jain tradition, Prince Neminatha abandoned his royal wedding in Junagadh upon hearing the cries of captive animals slated to be slaughtered for the wedding feast.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] His renunciation is said to be followed by his meditation at Mount Girnar.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] His refusal to predicate personal celebration upon animal slaughter served as a defining cultural catalyst.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Scholars identify this event as the foundational charter myth that shifted vegetarianism from an isolated ascetic exercise in self-denial into a universal ethical baseline regarding animal welfare for the entire Jain community.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] In Islam, animal rights were recognized early by the Sharia.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] This recognition is based on both the Qur'an and the Hadith.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] The Qur'an contains many references to animals, detailing that they have souls, form communities, communicate with God, and worship Him in their own way.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Muhammad forbade his followers to harm any animal and asked them to respect animals' rights.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Nevertheless, Islam does allow eating of certain species of animals.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] According to Christianity, all animals, from the smallest to the largest, are cared for and loved.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] According to the Bible, "All these animals waited for the Lord, that the Lord might give them food at the hour.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] The two main philosophical approaches to animal ethics are utilitarian and rights-based.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] The former is exemplified by Peter Singer, and the latter by Tom Regan and Gary Francione.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Deontologists argue that there are acts we should never perform, even if failing to do so entails a worse outcome.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] There are a number of positions that can be defended from a consequentalist or deontologist perspective, including the capabilities approach, represented by Martha Nussbaum, and the egalitarian approach, which has been examined by Ingmar Persson and Peter Vallentyne.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] The capabilities approach focuses on what individuals require to fulfill their capabilities: Nussbaum (2006) argues that animals need a right to life, some control over their environment, company, play, and physical health.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Clark, Mary Midgley, and Bernard Rollin also discuss animal rights in terms of animals being permitted to lead a life appropriate for their kind.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Egalitarianism favors an equal distribution of happiness among all individuals, which makes the interests of the worse off more important than those of the better off.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Another approach, virtue ethics, holds that in considering how to act we should consider the character of the actor, and what kind of moral agents we should be.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Rosalind Hursthouse has suggested an approach to animal rights based on virtue ethics.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Mark Rowlands has proposed a contractarian approach.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Nussbaum (2004) writes that utilitarianism, starting with Jeremy Bentham and John Stuart Mill, has contributed more to the recognition of the moral status of animals than any other ethical theory.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] The utilitarian philosopher most associated with animal rights is Peter Singer, professor of bioethics at Princeton University.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Singer is not a rights theorist, but uses the language of rights to discuss how we ought to treat individuals.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Until 2014, he was a preference utilitarian, meaning that he judged the rightness of an act by the extent to which it satisfies the preferences (interests) of those affected.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] His position is that there is no reason not to give equal consideration to the interests of human and nonhumans, though his principle of equality does not require identical treatment.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] A mouse and a man both have an interest in not being kicked, and there are no moral or logical grounds for failing to accord those interests equal weight.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Interests are predicated on the ability to suffer, nothing more, and once it is established that a being has interests, those interests must be given equal consideration.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Singer argues that equality of consideration is a prescription, not an assertion of fact: if the equality of the sexes were based only on the idea that men and women were equally intelligent, we would have to abandon the practice of equal consideration if this were later found to be false.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] But the moral idea of equality does not depend on matters of fact such as intelligence, physical strength, or moral capacity.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Equality therefore cannot be grounded on the outcome of scientific investigations into the intelligence of nonhumans.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] All that matters is whether they can suffer.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] People now accept that animals suffer and feel pain, but it was not always so.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Bernard Rollin, professor of philosophy, animal sciences, and biomedical sciences at Colorado State University, writes that Descartes's influence continued to be felt until the 1980s.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Veterinarians trained in the US before 1989 were taught to ignore pain, he writes, and at least one major veterinary hospital in the 1960s did not stock narcotic analgesics for animal pain control.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] In his interactions with scientists, he was often asked to "prove" that animals are conscious, and to provide "scientifically acceptable" evidence that they could feel pain.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] The ability of animals to suffer, even it may vary in severity, is the basis for Singer's application of equal consideration.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] The problem of animal suffering, and animal consciousness in general, arose primarily because it was argued that animals have no language.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Singer writes that, if language were needed to communicate pain, it would often be impossible to know when humans are in pain, though we can observe pain behavior and make a calculated guess based on it.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] He argues that there is no reason to suppose that the pain behavior of nonhumans would have a different meaning from the pain behavior of humans.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Tom Regan, professor emeritus of philosophy at North Carolina State University, argues in *The Case for Animal Rights* (1983) that nonhuman animals are what he calls "subjects-of-a-life", and as such are bearers of rights.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] He writes that, because the moral rights of humans are based on their possession of certain cognitive abilities, and because these abilities are also possessed by at least some nonhuman animals, such animals must have the same moral rights as humans.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Although only humans act as moral agents, both marginal-case humans, such as infants, and at least some nonhumans must have the status of "moral patients".
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Moral patients are unable to formulate moral principles, and as such are unable to do right or wrong, even though what they do may be beneficial or harmful.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Only moral agents are able to engage in moral action.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Animals for Regan have "intrinsic value" as subjects-of-a-life, and cannot be regarded as a means to an end, a view that places him firmly in the abolitionist camp.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] His theory does not extend to all animals, but only to those that can be regarded as subjects-of-a-life.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Whereas Singer is primarily concerned with improving the treatment of animals and accepts that, in some hypothetical scenarios, individual animals might be used legitimately to further human or nonhuman ends, Regan believes we ought to treat nonhuman animals as we would humans.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] He applies the strict Kantian ideal (which Kant himself applied only to humans) that they ought never to be sacrificed as a means to an end, and must be treated as ends in themselves.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Gary Francione, professor of law and philosophy at Rutgers Law School in Newark, is a leading abolitionist writer, arguing that animals need only one right, the right not to be owned.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Everything else would follow from that paradigm shift.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] He writes that, although most people would condemn the mistreatment of animals, and in many countries there are laws that seem to reflect those concerns, "in practice the legal system allows any use of animals, however abhorrent." The law only requires that any suffering not be "unnecessary".
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] In deciding what counts as "unnecessary", an animal's interests are weighed against the interests of human beings, and the latter almost always prevail.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Francione's *Animals, Property, and the Law* (1995) was the first extensive jurisprudential treatment of animal rights.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] In it, Francione compares the situation of animals to the treatment of slaves in the United States, where legislation existed that appeared to protect them while the courts ignored that the institution of slavery itself rendered the protection unenforceable.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] He offers as an example the United States Animal Welfare Act, which he describes as an example of symbolic legislation, intended to assuage public concern about the treatment of animals, but difficult to implement.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] He argues that a focus on animal welfare, rather than animal rights, may worsen the position of animals by making the public feel comfortable about using them and entrenching the view of them as property.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] His position in 1996 was that there is no animal rights movement in the United States.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Mark Rowlands, professor of philosophy at the University of Florida, has proposed a contractarian approach, based on the original position and the veil of ignorance—a "state of nature" thought experiment that tests intuitions about justice and fairness—in John Rawls's *A Theory of Justice* (1971).
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] The idea is that, operating behind the veil of ignorance, they will choose a social contract in which there is basic fairness and justice for them no matter the position they occupy.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Rawls did not include species membership as one of the attributes hidden from the decision-makers in the original position.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Rowlands proposes extending the veil of ignorance to include rationality, which he argues is an undeserved property similar to characteristics including race, sex and intelligence.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] American philosopher Timothy Garry has proposed an approach that deems nonhuman animals worthy of *prima facie* rights.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] In a philosophical context, a *prima facie* (Latin for "on the face of it" or "at first glance") right is one that appears to be applicable at first glance, but upon closer examination may be outweighed by other considerations.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] In his book *Ethics: A Pluralistic Approach to Moral Theory*, Lawrence Hinman characterizes such rights as "the right is real but leaves open the question of whether it is applicable and overriding in a particular situation".
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] The idea that nonhuman animals are worthy of *prima facie* rights is to say that, in a sense, animals have rights that can be overridden by many other considerations, especially those conflicting a human's right to life, liberty, property, and the pursuit of happiness.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] In sum, Garry suggests that humans have obligations to nonhuman animals; animals do not, and ought not to, have uninfringible rights against humans.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Women have played a central role in animal advocacy since the 19th century.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] The anti-vivisection movement in the 19th and early 20th century in England and the United States was largely run by women, including Frances Power Cobbe, Anna Kingsford, Lizzy Lind af Hageby and Caroline Earle White (1833–1916).
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Garner writes that 70 per cent of the membership of the Victoria Street Society (one of the anti-vivisection groups founded by Cobbe) were women, as were 70 per cent of the membership of the British RSPCA in 1900.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] The modern animal advocacy movement has a similar representation of women.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] They are not invariably in leadership positions: during the March for Animals in Washington, D.C., in 1990—the largest animal rights demonstration held until then in the United States—most of the participants were women, but most of the platform speakers were men.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] In the Netherlands, Marianne Thieme and Esther Ouwehand were elected to parliament in 2006 representing the Parliamentary group for Animals.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Lori Gruen writes that women and animals serve the same symbolic function in a patriarchal society: both are "the used"; the dominated, submissive "Other".
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] In her works *The Sexual Politics of Meat: A Feminist-Vegetarian Critical Theory* (1990) and *The Pornography of Meat* (2004), Carol J.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Adams focuses in particular on what she argues are the links between the oppression of women and that of non-human animals.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Some transhumanists argue for animal rights, liberation, and "uplift" of animal consciousness into machines.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Transhumanism also understands animal rights on a gradation or spectrum with other types of sentient rights, including human rights and the rights of conscious artificial intelligences (posthuman rights).
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] According to sociologist David Nibert of Wittenberg University, the struggle for animal liberation must happen in tandem with a more generalized struggle against human oppression and exploitation under global capitalism.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] According to sociologist Richard Twine, animals themselves serve as producers and product for human consumption within a global capitalist system.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] He believes that the capitalist system exploits animals as a producer and a product, which he calls the "profoundly speciesist animal-industrial complex".
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Many members of Germany's Nazi Party were proponents of vegetarianism and animal rights.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Adolf Hitler regarded himself as a vegetarian, and according to a transcript of one of Hitler's Table Talks, he said "the world of the future will be vegetarian." Other radical proponents of animal rights included Hindu writer Savitri Devi, the author of Impeachment of Man.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Today there is a growing ecofascist movement influenced by past rightist commentators that incorporates animal rights into its ideology.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Frey, professor of philosophy at Bowling Green State University, is a preference utilitarian.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] In his early work, *Interests and Rights* (1980), Frey disagreed with Singer—who wrote in *Animal Liberation* (1975) that the interests of nonhuman animals must be given equal consideration when judging the consequences of an act—on the grounds that animals have no interests.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Frey argues that interests are dependent on desire, and that no desire can exist without a corresponding belief.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Animals have no beliefs, because a belief state requires the ability to hold a second-order belief—a belief about the belief—which he argues requires language: "If someone were to say, e.g.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Carl Cohen, professor of philosophy at the University of Michigan, argues that rights holders must be able to distinguish between their own interests and what is right.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] "The holders of rights must have the capacity to comprehend rules of duty governing all, including themselves.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] In applying such rules, [they] ... must recognize possible conflicts between what is in their own interest and what is just.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Cohen writes that the test for moral judgment "is not a test to be administered to humans one by one", but should be applied to the capacity of members of the species in general.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Judge Richard Posner of the United States Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit debated the issue of animal rights in 2001 with Peter Singer.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Posner posits that his moral intuition tells him "that human beings prefer their own.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] If a dog threatens a human infant, even if it requires causing more pain to the dog to stop it, than the dog would have caused to the infant, then we favour the child.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Singer challenges this by arguing that formerly unequal rights for gays, women, and certain races were justified using the same set of intuitions.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Posner replies that equality in civil rights did not occur because of ethical arguments, but because facts mounted that there were no morally significant differences between humans based on race, sex, or sexual orientation that would support inequality.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] If and when similar facts emerge about humans and animals, the differences in rights will erode too.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] But facts will drive equality, not ethical arguments that run contrary to instinct, he argues.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Posner calls his approach "soft utilitarianism", in contrast to Singer's "hard utilitarianism".
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Roger Scruton, the British philosopher, argued that rights imply obligations.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] He accused animal rights advocates of "pre-scientific" anthropomorphism, attributing traits to animals that are, he says, Beatrix Potter-like, where "only man is vile." It is within this fiction that the appeal of animal rights lies, he argued.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] The world of animals is non-judgmental, filled with dogs who return our affection almost no matter what we do to them, and cats who pretend to be affectionate when, in fact, they care only about themselves.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] It is, he argued, a fantasy, a world of escape.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Scruton singled out Peter Singer, a prominent Australian philosopher and animal-rights activist, for criticism.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] He wrote that Singer's works, including *Animal Liberation*, "contain little or no philosophical argument.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Tom Regan countered this view of rights by distinguishing moral agents and moral patients.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] According to a 2000 paper by Harold Herzog and Lorna Dorr, previous academic surveys of attitudes toward animal rights tended to have small sample sizes and non-representative groups.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] But a number of factors appear to correlate with people's attitudes about the treatment of animals and animal rights.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] These include gender, age, occupation, religion, and level of education.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] There is also evidence suggesting that experience with pets may be a factor in people's attitudes.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] According to some studies, women are more likely to empathize with the cause of animal rights than men.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] A 1996 study suggested that factors that may partially explain this discrepancy include attitudes towards feminism and science, scientific literacy, and the presence of a greater emphasis on "nurturance or compassion" among women.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] A common misconception about animal rights is that its proponents want to grant nonhuman animals the same legal rights as humans, such as the right to vote.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Rather, the idea is that animals should have rights that accord with their interests (for example, cats have no interest in voting, and so should not have the right to vote).
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] A 2016 study found that support for animal testing may not be based on cogent philosophical rationales and that more open debate is warranted.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] The findings extended previous research, such as a 1992 study that found that 48% of animal rights activists were atheists or agnostic.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] A 2019 *Washington Post* study found that those with favorable attitudes toward animal rights also tend to have favorable views of universal healthcare; reducing discrimination against African Americans, the LGBT community, and undocumented immigrants; and expanding welfare to aid the poor.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Two surveys found that attitudes toward animal rights tactics, such as direct action, are very diverse within the animal rights communities.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Near half (50% and 39% in two surveys) of activists do not support direct action.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] In the U.S., the National Farmers Organization held many public protest slaughters in the late 1960s and early 1970s.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] Protesting low prices for meat, farmers killed their animals in front of media representatives.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] The carcasses were wasted and not eaten.
[src:animal-rights/animal-rights] This effort backfired because it angered people to see animals needlessly and wastefully killed.
